# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: andrew-lawson
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:andrew-lawson/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] A magnitude 7.9 earthquake struck the coast of Northern California at 05:12 am Pacific Standard Time on Wednesday, April 18, 1906.
[src:andrew-lawson/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] With a maximum Mercalli intensity of XI (*Extreme*), it created high-intensity shaking from Eureka on the North Coast to the Salinas Valley, an agricultural region to the south of the San Francisco Bay Area.
[src:andrew-lawson/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Extensive fires soon broke out in San Francisco and lasted for several days.
[src:andrew-lawson/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] More than 3,000 people died and over 80% of the city was destroyed.
[src:andrew-lawson/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] The event is remembered as the deadliest earthquake in the history of the United States.
[src:andrew-lawson/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] The death toll remains the greatest loss of life from a natural disaster in California's history and high on the list of worst American disasters, natural or man-made.
[src:andrew-lawson/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] The San Andreas Fault is a continental transform fault that forms part of the tectonic boundary between the Pacific plate and the North American plate.
[src:andrew-lawson/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] The strike-slip fault is characterized by mainly lateral motion in a dextral sense, where the western (Pacific) plate moves northward relative to the eastern (North American) plate.
[src:andrew-lawson/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] This fault runs the length of California from the Salton Sea in the south to Cape Mendocino in the north, a distance of about 810 miles (1,300 km).
[src:andrew-lawson/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] The maximum observed surface displacement was about 20 feet (6 m); geodetic measurements show displacements of up to 28 feet (8.5 m).
[src:andrew-lawson/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] The 1906 earthquake preceded the development of the Richter scale.
[src:andrew-lawson/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] The most widely accepted estimate for the magnitude of the quake on the modern moment magnitude scale is 7.9; values from 7.7 to as high as 8.3 have been proposed.
[src:andrew-lawson/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] According to findings published in the *Journal of Geophysical Research*, severe deformations in the Earth's crust took place both before and after the earthquake's impact.
[src:andrew-lawson/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Accumulated strain on the faults in the system was relieved during the earthquake, which is the supposed cause of the damage along the 280-mile-long (450 km) segment of the San Andreas plate boundary.
[src:andrew-lawson/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] The 1906 rupture propagated both northward and southward for a total of 296 miles (476 km).
[src:andrew-lawson/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Shaking was felt from Oregon to Los Angeles, and as far inland as central Nevada.
[src:andrew-lawson/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] A strong foreshock preceded the main shock by about 20 to 25 seconds.
[src:andrew-lawson/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] The strong shaking of the main shock lasted about 42 seconds.
[src:andrew-lawson/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] There were decades of minor earthquakes – more than at any other time in the historical record for northern California – before the 1906 quake.
[src:andrew-lawson/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] For years, the epicenter of the quake was assumed to be near the town of Olema, in the Point Reyes area of Marin County, due to local earth displacement measurements.
[src:andrew-lawson/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] In the 1960s, a seismologist at UC Berkeley proposed that the epicenter was more likely offshore of San Francisco, to the northwest of the Golden Gate.
[src:andrew-lawson/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] The most recent analyses support an offshore location for the epicenter, although significant uncertainty remains.
[src:andrew-lawson/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] An offshore epicenter is supported by the occurrence of a local tsunami recorded by a tide gauge at the San Francisco Presidio; the wave had an amplitude of approximately 3 inches (7.6 cm) and an approximate period of 40–45 minutes.
[src:andrew-lawson/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Analysis of triangulation data before and after the earthquake strongly suggests that the rupture along the San Andreas Fault was about 310 miles (500 km) in length, in agreement with observed intensity data.
[src:andrew-lawson/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] The available seismological data support a significantly shorter rupture length, but these observations can be reconciled by allowing propagation at speeds above the S-wave velocity (supershear).
[src:andrew-lawson/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Supershear propagation has now been recognized for many earthquakes associated with strike-slip faulting.
[src:andrew-lawson/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] In 2019, using an old photograph and a recorded eyewitness account, researchers were able to refine the location of the hypocenter of the earthquake as offshore from San Francisco or near San Juan Bautista, confirming previous estimates.
[src:andrew-lawson/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] The shaking intensity as described on the Modified Mercalli intensity scale reached XI (*Extreme*) in San Francisco and areas to the north like Santa Rosa where destruction was devastating.
[src:andrew-lawson/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] The most important characteristic of the shaking intensity noted in Andrew Lawson's 1908 report was the clear correlation of intensity with underlying geologic conditions.
[src:andrew-lawson/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Areas situated in sediment-filled valleys sustained stronger shaking than nearby bedrock sites, and the strongest shaking occurred in areas of former bay where soil liquefaction had occurred.
[src:andrew-lawson/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Modern seismic-zonation practice accounts for the differences in hazard posed by varying geologic conditions.
[src:andrew-lawson/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] The main shock was followed by many aftershocks and some remotely triggered events.
[src:andrew-lawson/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] As with the 1857 Fort Tejon earthquake, there were fewer aftershocks than would have been expected for a shock of that size.
[src:andrew-lawson/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Very few of them were located along the trace of the 1906 rupture, tending to concentrate near the ends of the rupture or on other structures away from the San Andreas Fault, such as the Hayward Fault.
[src:andrew-lawson/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] The only aftershock in the first few days of near MI 5 or greater occurred near Santa Cruz at 14:28 PST on April 18, with a magnitude of about 4.9 M.
[src:andrew-lawson/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] The largest aftershock happened at 01:10 PST on April 23, west of Eureka with an estimated magnitude of about 6.7 MI, with another of the same size more than three years later at 22:45 PST on October 28 near Cape Mendocino.
[src:andrew-lawson/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Remotely triggered events included an earthquake swarm in the Imperial Valley area, which culminated in an earthquake of about 6.1 MI at 16:30 PST on April 18, 1906.
[src:andrew-lawson/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Another event of this type occurred at 12:31 PST on April 19, 1906, with an estimated magnitude of about 5.0 MI, and an epicenter beneath Santa Monica Bay.
[src:andrew-lawson/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Seismographs on the U.S. east coast recorded the earthquake some 19 minutes later.
[src:andrew-lawson/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Some early death estimates exceeded 500.
[src:andrew-lawson/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Early death counts ranged from 375 to over 500.
[src:andrew-lawson/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] However, hundreds of fatalities in Chinatown went ignored and unrecorded.
[src:andrew-lawson/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] The total number of deaths is still uncertain, but various reports presented a range of 700–3,000+.
[src:andrew-lawson/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] In 2005, the city's Board of Supervisors voted unanimously in support of a resolution written by novelist James Dalessandro ("1906") and city historian Gladys Hansen ("Denial of Disaster") to recognize the figure of 3,000+ as the official total.
[src:andrew-lawson/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Most of the deaths occurred within San Francisco, but 189 were reported elsewhere in the Bay Area; nearby cities such as Santa Rosa and San Jose also suffered severe damage.
[src:andrew-lawson/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Between 227,000 and 300,000 people were left homeless out of a population of about 410,000; half of those who evacuated fled across the bay to Oakland and Berkeley.
[src:andrew-lawson/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Newspapers described Golden Gate Park, the Presidio, the Panhandle and the beaches between Ingleside and North Beach as covered with makeshift tents.
[src:andrew-lawson/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] More than two years later, many of these refugee camps were still in operation.
[src:andrew-lawson/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] The earthquake and fire left long-standing and significant pressures on the development of California.
[src:andrew-lawson/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] At the time of the disaster, San Francisco had been the ninth-largest city in the United States and the largest on the West Coast.
[src:andrew-lawson/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Over a period of 60 years, the city had become the financial, trade, and cultural center of the West, operating the busiest port on the West Coast.
[src:andrew-lawson/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] It was the "gateway to the Pacific", through which growing U.S. economic and military power was projected into the Pacific and Asia.
[src:andrew-lawson/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Over 80% of the city was destroyed by the earthquake and fire.
[src:andrew-lawson/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Though San Francisco rebuilt quickly, the disaster diverted trade, industry, and population growth south to Los Angeles, which during the 20th century became the largest and most important urban area in the West.
[src:andrew-lawson/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Many of the city's leading poets and writers retreated to Carmel-by-the-Sea where, as "The Barness", they established the arts colony reputation that continues today.
[src:andrew-lawson/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] The 1908 Lawson Report, a study of the 1906 quake led and edited by Professor Andrew Lawson of the University of California, showed that the same San Andreas Fault which had caused the disaster in San Francisco ran close to Los Angeles as well.
[src:andrew-lawson/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] The earthquake was the first natural disaster of its magnitude to be documented by photography and motion picture footage and occurred at a time when the science of seismology was blossoming.
[src:andrew-lawson/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Writing from San Francisco on April 23, five days after the earthquake, resident John W.
[src:andrew-lawson/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Nourse described the scene to his family in Indiana: woken at quarter past five by shaking that made the house "seem like it would break all to pieces," he looked out to see a large brick building completely destroyed in seconds, with fires visible simultaneously to the right, front, and left.
[src:andrew-lawson/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Grabbing the baby's buggy, he and his wife Lena fled to Market Street, which he described as a terrible sight.
[src:andrew-lawson/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Whole blocks reduced to masses of ruins, City Hall a complete wreck.
[src:andrew-lawson/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] He left his wife and baby at the mission and returned to try to save their belongings, but found the whole part of the city burning.
[src:andrew-lawson/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] "In traveling over the city it looks like there is not a building but what is more or less damaged," he wrote.
[src:andrew-lawson/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] A traveler passing through San Francisco ten days after the earthquake, Mrs.
[src:andrew-lawson/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Baughman of LeMars, Iowa, described a stove placed in front of every house, residents were not permitted to cook indoors, and Market Street sunken several feet in places, with one point four blocks from the Ferry five feet lower than the sidewalk and the cable car rails warped and twisted.
[src:andrew-lawson/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] She observed soldiers with blue coats throughout the begrimed crowds, groups of listless dazed men in the suburbs, and frame buildings near Valencia Street completely shattered within a radius of several blocks.
[src:andrew-lawson/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Writing from Boulder Creek, eighty miles south of San Francisco, former journalist Mathias Forestburg described being violently awakened by the shaking, the house rocking like a boat with timbers creaking and everything thrown to the floor.
[src:andrew-lawson/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] He spent the morning dismantling a cracked chimney that was balanced on three bricks.
[src:andrew-lawson/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] One more aftershock would have brought it down and demolished the house.
[src:andrew-lawson/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] He reported continual shaking every day and night since the earthquake, keeping the community on constant alert, and noted that all business had stopped and all who could afford to leave were going east.
[src:andrew-lawson/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] The most immediate firsthand account came from Lewis A.
[src:andrew-lawson/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Spitzer of San Jose, who wrote to his brother-in-law in Virginia at midnight on the day of the earthquake itself.
[src:andrew-lawson/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Spitzer had been staying at a mineral spring in the mountains the previous night; waking just before 5 AM, he was thrown against the wall at 5:15 as the shock struck while he was putting a pan of water on the stove.
[src:andrew-lawson/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Electric cars had stopped running and he hired a farmer to bring him home by buggy.
[src:andrew-lawson/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] He found his house standing with only cracked plaster, but described San Jose as "in ruins.
[src:andrew-lawson/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Fine business houses flat on the ground" and San Francisco as nearly all in ruins and in flames.
[src:andrew-lawson/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] His son-in-law had arrived from San Francisco reporting that Spitzer's son and his wife and baby appeared to have escaped safely, but the family could not reach them.
[src:andrew-lawson/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] The streets were full of people camping in tents, some without tents, afraid to go indoors.
[src:andrew-lawson/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] "I have seen many heart rending scenes in my life," he wrote, "but never any such a terrible scene as this.
[src:andrew-lawson/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Although the impact of the earthquake on San Francisco was the most famous, the earthquake also inflicted considerable damage on several other cities.
[src:andrew-lawson/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] These include San Jose and Santa Rosa, the entire downtown of which was essentially destroyed.
[src:andrew-lawson/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Duffy of Owensboro, Kentucky, who had been staying at the St.
[src:andrew-lawson/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Rose Hotel in Santa Rosa, reported being trapped for five hours in the ruins before rescuers reached him.
[src:andrew-lawson/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] He finally made his location known by poking a lath through a hole left by a falling steam pipe.
[src:andrew-lawson/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] As damaging as the earthquake and its aftershocks were, the fires that burned out of control afterward were far more destructive.
[src:andrew-lawson/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] It has been estimated that at least 80%, and at most over 95%, of the total destruction was the result of the subsequent fires.
[src:andrew-lawson/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Within three days, over 30 fires, that were caused by ruptured gas mains, destroyed approximately 25,000 buildings on 490 city blocks.
[src:andrew-lawson/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] The fires cost an estimated $350 million at the time (equivalent to $9.1 billion in 2024).
[src:andrew-lawson/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] The *Ham and Eggs* fire, in the morning on the 18th, at Hayes and Gough Streets, in Hayes Valley, was started by a woman who lit her stove to prepare breakfast, unaware of the badly damaged chimney, destroying a 30-block area, including a college, the Hall of Records and City Hall.
[src:andrew-lawson/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Some of the fires were started when San Francisco Fire Department firefighters, untrained in the use of dynamite, attempted to demolish buildings to create firebreaks.
[src:andrew-lawson/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] The dynamited buildings often caught fire.
[src:andrew-lawson/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Sullivan, who would have been responsible for coordinating firefighting efforts, had died from injuries sustained in the initial quake.
[src:andrew-lawson/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] In total, the fires burned for four days and nights.
[src:andrew-lawson/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Most of the destruction in the city was attributed to the fires, since widespread practice by insurers was to indemnify San Francisco properties from fire but not from earthquake damage.
[src:andrew-lawson/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Army Signal Corps reported that he "was stopped by a fireman who told me that people in that neighborhood were firing their houses...they were told that they would not get their insurance on buildings damaged by the earthquake unless they were damaged by fire".
[src:andrew-lawson/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] One landmark building lost in the fire was the Palace Hotel, subsequently rebuilt, which had many famous visitors including royalty and celebrated performers.
[src:andrew-lawson/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] It was constructed in 1875 primarily financed by Bank of California co-founder William Ralston, the "man who built San Francisco".
[src:andrew-lawson/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] In April 1906, the tenor Enrico Caruso and members of the Metropolitan Opera Company came to San Francisco to give a series of performances at the Grand Opera House.
[src:andrew-lawson/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] The night after Caruso's performance in *Carmen*, the tenor was awakened in the early morning in his Palace Hotel suite by a strong jolt.
[src:andrew-lawson/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Clutching an autographed photo of President Theodore Roosevelt, Caruso made an effort to get out of the city, first by boat and then by train, and vowed never to return.
[src:andrew-lawson/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] The Metropolitan Opera Company lost all of its traveling sets and costumes.
[src:andrew-lawson/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Some of the greatest losses from fire were in scientific laboratories.
[src:andrew-lawson/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Alice Eastwood, the curator of botany at the California Academy of Sciences in San Francisco, is credited with saving the entire plant type specimen collection of the Academy before the remainder of the largest botanical collection in the western United States was destroyed in the fire.
[src:andrew-lawson/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] The entire laboratory and all the records of Benjamin R.
[src:andrew-lawson/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Jacobs, a biochemist who was researching the nutrition of everyday foods, were destroyed.
[src:andrew-lawson/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] The original California flag used in the 1846 Bear Flag Revolt at Sonoma, stored in a state building in San Francisco, was also destroyed in the fire.
[src:andrew-lawson/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Sullivan, was gravely injured when the earthquake first struck and later died from his injuries.
[src:andrew-lawson/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Sullivan and his wife had been sleeping in the engine house adjoining the California Hotel on Bush Street when bricks crashed through the roof.
[src:andrew-lawson/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] The interim fire chief sent an urgent request to the Presidio for dynamite.
[src:andrew-lawson/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] General Frederick Funston had already decided that the situation required the use of federal troops.
[src:andrew-lawson/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Telephoning a San Francisco Police Department officer, he sent word to Mayor Eugene Schmitz of his decision to assist and then ordered federal troops from nearby Angel Island to mobilize and enter the city.
[src:andrew-lawson/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Explosives were ferried across the bay from the California Powder Works in what is now Hercules.
[src:andrew-lawson/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] During the first few days, soldiers provided valuable services like patrolling streets to discourage looting and guarding buildings such as the U.S.
[src:andrew-lawson/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] They aided the fire department in dynamiting to demolish buildings in the path of the fires.
[src:andrew-lawson/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] The Army also became responsible for feeding, sheltering, and clothing the tens of thousands of displaced residents of the city.
[src:andrew-lawson/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Under the command of Funston's superior, Major General Adolphus Greely, Commanding Officer of the Pacific Division, over 4,000 federal troops saw service during the emergency.
[src:andrew-lawson/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Police officers, firefighters, and soldiers would regularly commandeer passing civilians for work details to remove rubble and assist in rescues.
[src:andrew-lawson/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] On July 1, 1906, non-military authorities assumed responsibility for relief efforts, and the Army withdrew from the city.
[src:andrew-lawson/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Accusations of soldiers engaging in looting also surfaced.
[src:andrew-lawson/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Retired Captain Edward Ord of the 22nd Infantry Regiment was appointed a special police officer by Schmitz and liaised with Greely for relief work with the 22nd Infantry and other military units involved in the emergency.
[src:andrew-lawson/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Ord later wrote a long letter to his mother on April 20 regarding Schmitz's "Shoot-to-Kill" order and some "despicable" behavior of certain soldiers of the 22nd Infantry who were looting.
[src:andrew-lawson/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] He also made it clear that the majority of soldiers served the community well.
[src:andrew-lawson/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Property losses from the disaster have been estimated to be more than $400 million in 1906 dollars.
[src:andrew-lawson/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] This is equivalent to $10.4 billion in 2024 dollars.
[src:andrew-lawson/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] An insurance industry source tallies insured losses at $235 million, the equivalent to $6.13 billion in 2024 dollars.
[src:andrew-lawson/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Political and business leaders strongly downplayed the effects of the earthquake, fearing loss of outside investment in the city which was badly needed to rebuild.
[src:andrew-lawson/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] The earthquake is not even mentioned in the statement.
[src:andrew-lawson/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Fatality and monetary damage estimates were manipulated.
[src:andrew-lawson/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Almost immediately after the quake (and even during the disaster), planning and reconstruction plans were hatched to quickly rebuild the city.
[src:andrew-lawson/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Rebuilding funds were immediately tied up by the fact that virtually all the major banks had been sites of the conflagration, requiring a lengthy wait of seven to ten days before their fire-proof vaults could cool sufficiently to be safely opened.
[src:andrew-lawson/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] The Bank of Italy (now Bank of America) had evacuated its funds and was able to provide liquidity in the immediate aftermath.
[src:andrew-lawson/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Its president also immediately chartered and financed the sending of two ships to return with shiploads of lumber from Washington and Oregon mills which provided the initial reconstruction materials and surge.
[src:andrew-lawson/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Branner, who was the first to begin study of the San Andreas fault in 1891 complained that the Federal Government of the United States had not conducted the serious studies that were needed to gather data about earthquakes on the west coast.
[src:andrew-lawson/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] He said public discussion was being stifled by fears that acknowledgement of earthquakes would drive away business and investors, and that geologists were told not to gather information about the 1906 earthquake, and certainly to not publish it.
[src:andrew-lawson/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Some people went as far as to deny that an earthquake had happened.
[src:andrew-lawson/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Eleven days after the earthquake a rare Sunday baseball game was played in New York City (which would not allow regular Sunday baseball until 1919) between the Highlanders (soon to be the Yankees) and the Philadelphia Athletics to raise money for quake survivors.
[src:andrew-lawson/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] William James, the pioneering American psychologist, was teaching at Stanford at the time of the earthquake and traveled into San Francisco to observe first-hand its aftermath.
[src:andrew-lawson/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] He was most impressed by the positive attitude of the survivors and the speed with which they improvised services and created order out of chaos.
[src:andrew-lawson/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] This formed the basis of the chapter "On some Mental Effects of the Earthquake" in his book *Memories and Studies*.
[src:andrew-lawson/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Wells had just arrived in New York on his first visit to America when he learned of the San Francisco earthquake.
[src:andrew-lawson/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] What struck him about the reaction of those around him was that "it does not seem to have affected any one with a sense of final destruction, with any foreboding of irreparable disaster.
[src:andrew-lawson/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Every one is talking of it this afternoon, and no one is in the least degree dismayed.
[src:andrew-lawson/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] I have talked and listened in two clubs, watched people in cars and in the street, and one man is glad that Chinatown will be cleared out for good; another's chief solicitude is for Millet's *Man with a Hoe*.
[src:andrew-lawson/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] 'They'll cut it out of the frame,' he says, a little anxiously.
[src:andrew-lawson/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] 'Sure.' But there is no doubt anywhere that San Francisco can be rebuilt, larger, better, and soon.
[src:andrew-lawson/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Just as there would be none at all if all this New York that has so obsessed me with its limitless bigness was itself a blazing ruin.
[src:andrew-lawson/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] The earthquake was crucial in the development of the University of California, San Francisco and its medical facilities.
[src:andrew-lawson/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Until 1906, the school faculty had provided care at the City-County Hospital (now the San Francisco General Hospital), but did not have a hospital of its own.
[src:andrew-lawson/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Following the 1906 San Francisco earthquake, more than 40,000 people were relocated to a makeshift tent city in Golden Gate Park and were treated by the faculty of the Affiliated Colleges.
[src:andrew-lawson/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] This brought the school, which until then was located on the western outskirts of the city, in contact with significant population and fueled the commitment of the school towards civic responsibility and health care, increasing the momentum towards the construction of its own health facilities.
[src:andrew-lawson/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] In April 1907, one of the buildings was renovated for outpatient care with 75 beds.
[src:andrew-lawson/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] This created the need to train nursing students, and the UC Training School for Nurses was established, adding a fourth professional school to the Affiliated Colleges.
[src:andrew-lawson/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] The grandeur of citywide reconstruction schemes required investment from Eastern monetary sources, hence the spin and de-emphasis of the earthquake, the promulgation of the tough new building codes, and subsequent reputation sensitive actions such as the official low death toll.
[src:andrew-lawson/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] One of the more famous and ambitious plans came from famed urban planner Daniel Burnham.
[src:andrew-lawson/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] But this plan was dismissed during the aftermath of the earthquake.
[src:andrew-lawson/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] For example, real estate investors and other land owners were against the idea because of the large amount of land the city would have to purchase to realize such proposals.
[src:andrew-lawson/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Limestone used to reconstruct city buildings was quarried at the nearby Rockaway Quarry.
[src:andrew-lawson/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] City fathers likewise attempted at the time to eliminate the Chinese population and export Chinatown (and other poor populations) to the edge of the county where the Chinese could still contribute to the local taxbase.
[src:andrew-lawson/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] The Chinese occupants had other ideas and prevailed instead.
[src:andrew-lawson/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Chinatown was rebuilt in the newer, modern, Western form that exists today.
[src:andrew-lawson/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] The destruction of City Hall and the Hall of Records enabled thousands of Chinese immigrants to claim residency and citizenship, creating a backdoor to the Chinese Exclusion Act, and bring in their relatives from China.
[src:andrew-lawson/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] The earthquake was also responsible for the development of the Pacific Heights neighborhood.
[src:andrew-lawson/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] The immense power of the earthquake had destroyed almost all of the mansions on Nob Hill except for the James C.
[src:andrew-lawson/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Others that had not been destroyed were dynamited by the Army forces aiding the firefighting efforts in attempts to create firebreaks.
[src:andrew-lawson/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] As one indirect result, the wealthy looked westward where the land was cheap and relatively undeveloped, and where there were better views.
[src:andrew-lawson/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Constructing new mansions without reclaiming and clearing rubble simply sped attaining new homes in the tent city during the reconstruction.
[src:andrew-lawson/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Reconstruction was swift, and largely completed by 1915, in time for the 1915 Panama–Pacific International Exposition which celebrated the reconstruction of the city and its "rise from the ashes".
[src:andrew-lawson/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Since 1915, the city has officially commemorated the disaster each year by gathering the remaining survivors at Lotta's Fountain, a fountain in the city's financial district that served as a meeting point during the disaster for people to look for loved ones and exchange information.
[src:andrew-lawson/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] The Army built 5,610 redwood and fir "relief houses" to accommodate 20,000 displaced people.
[src:andrew-lawson/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] The houses were designed by John McLaren, and were grouped in 11 camps, packed close to each other and rented to people for two dollars per month until rebuilding was completed.
[src:andrew-lawson/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] They were painted navy blue, partly to blend in with the site and partly because the military had large quantities of navy blue paint on hand.
[src:andrew-lawson/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] The camps had a peak population of 16,448 people, but by 1907 most people had moved out.
[src:andrew-lawson/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] The camps were then re-used as garages, storage spaces or shops.
[src:andrew-lawson/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] The cottages cost on average $100 to build.
[src:andrew-lawson/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] The $2 monthly rents went towards the full purchase price of $50.
[src:andrew-lawson/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] The last official refugee camp was closed on June 30, 1908.
[src:andrew-lawson/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Most of the cottages have been destroyed, but at least 30 survived.
[src:andrew-lawson/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Of the remaining structures, there is a historically restored pair in the Presidio.
[src:andrew-lawson/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Others have been built on as part of private homes, with a high concentration around the Bernal Heights neighborhood.
[src:andrew-lawson/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] One of the modest 720 sq ft (67 m2) homes was purchased in 2006 for more than $600,000.
[src:andrew-lawson/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] A 2017 study found that the fire had the effect of increasing the share of land used for nonresidential purposes: "Overall, relative to unburned blocks, residential land shares on burned blocks fell while nonresidential land shares rose by 1931.
[src:andrew-lawson/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] The study also provides insight into what held the city back from making these changes before 1906: the presence of old residential buildings.
[src:andrew-lawson/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] In reconstruction, developers built relatively fewer of these buildings, and the majority of the reduction came through single-family houses.
[src:andrew-lawson/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Aside from merely expanding nonresidential uses in many neighborhoods, the fire created economic opportunities in new areas, resulting in clusters of business activity that emerged only in the wake of the disaster.
[src:andrew-lawson/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] During the first few days after news of the disaster reached the rest of the world, relief efforts reached over $5,000,000, equivalent to $179,170,000 in 2025.
[src:andrew-lawson/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] London raised hundreds of thousands of dollars.
[src:andrew-lawson/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Individual citizens and businesses donated large sums of money for the relief effort: Standard Oil and Andrew Carnegie each gave $100,000; the Parliament of Canada made a special appropriation of $100,000; and even the Bank of Canada in Ottawa gave $25,000.
[src:andrew-lawson/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] The United States Congress quickly appropriated 2.5 million dollars for relief supplies which were immediately rushed to the area, including supplies for food kitchens and many thousands of tents that city dwellers would occupy the next several years.
[src:andrew-lawson/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] These relief efforts were not enough to get families on their feet again, and consequently the burden was placed on wealthier members of the city, who were reluctant to assist in the rebuilding of homes they were not responsible for.
[src:andrew-lawson/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] All residents were eligible for daily meals served from a number of communal soup kitchens, and citizens as far away as Idaho and Utah were known to send daily loaves of bread to San Francisco as relief supplies were coordinated by the railroads.
[src:andrew-lawson/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Insurance companies, faced with staggering claims of $250 million, paid out between $235 million and $265 million on policyholders' claims, often for fire damage only, since shake damage from earthquakes was excluded from coverage under most policies.
[src:andrew-lawson/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] At least 137 insurance companies were directly involved and another 17 as reinsurers.
[src:andrew-lawson/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Lloyd's of London reports having paid all claims in full, more than $50 million, thanks to the leadership of Cuthbert Heath.
[src:andrew-lawson/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Insurance companies in Hartford, Connecticut, report paying every claim in full, with the Hartford Fire Insurance Company paying over $11 million and Aetna Insurance Company almost $3 million.
[src:andrew-lawson/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] The insurance payments heavily affected the international financial system.
[src:andrew-lawson/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Gold transfers from European insurance companies to policyholders in San Francisco led to a rise in interest rates, subsequently to a lack of available loans and finally to the Knickerbocker Trust Company crisis of October 1907 which led to the Panic of 1907.
[src:andrew-lawson/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] After the 1906 earthquake, global discussion arose concerning a legally flawless exclusion of the earthquake hazard from fire insurance contracts.
[src:andrew-lawson/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] It was pressed ahead mainly by re-insurers.
[src:andrew-lawson/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Their aim: a uniform solution to insurance payouts resulting from fires caused by earthquakes.
[src:andrew-lawson/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Until 1910, a few countries, especially in Europe, followed the call for an exclusion of the earthquake hazard from all fire insurance contracts.
[src:andrew-lawson/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] In the U.S., the question was discussed differently.
[src:andrew-lawson/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] But the traumatized public reacted with fierce opposition.
[src:andrew-lawson/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] In the second half of 1909, the California State Legislature enacted the California Standard Form of Fire Insurance Policy, which did not contain any earthquake clause.
[src:andrew-lawson/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Thus the state decided that insurers would have to pay again if another earthquake was followed by fires.
[src:andrew-lawson/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Other earthquake-endangered countries followed the California example.
[src:andrew-lawson/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] The 1906 Centennial Alliance was set up as a clearing-house for various centennial events commemorating the earthquake.
[src:andrew-lawson/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Award presentations, religious services, a National Geographic TV movie, a projection of fire onto the Coit Tower, memorials, and lectures were part of the commemorations.
[src:andrew-lawson/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] The USGS Earthquake Hazards Program issued a series of Internet documents, and the tourism industry promoted the 100th anniversary as well.
[src:andrew-lawson/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Eleven survivors of the 1906 earthquake attended the centennial commemorations in 2006, including Irma Mae Weule (1899–2008), who was the oldest survivor of the quake at the time of her death in August 2008, aged 109.
[src:andrew-lawson/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Vivian Illing (1900–2009) was believed to be the second-oldest survivor at the time of her death, aged 108, leaving Herbert Hamrol (1903–2009) as the last known remaining survivor at the time of his death, aged 106.
[src:andrew-lawson/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Another survivor, Libera Armstrong (1902–2007), attended the 2006 anniversary but died in 2007, aged 105.
[src:andrew-lawson/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Shortly after Hamrol's death, two additional survivors were discovered.
[src:andrew-lawson/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] William Del Monte, then 103, and Jeanette Scola Trapani (1902–2009), 106, stated that they stopped attending events commemorating the earthquake when it became too much trouble for them.
[src:andrew-lawson/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Del Monte and another survivor, Rose Cliver (1902–2012), then 106, attended the earthquake reunion celebration on April 18, 2009, the 103rd anniversary of the earthquake.
[src:andrew-lawson/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Nancy Stoner Sage (1905–2010) died, aged 105, in Colorado just three days short of the 104th anniversary of the earthquake on April 18, 2010.
[src:andrew-lawson/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Del Monte attended the event at Lotta's Fountain in 2010.
[src:andrew-lawson/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] William Del Monte (1906–2016), who died 11 days shy of his 110th birthday, was thought to be the last survivor.
[src:andrew-lawson/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] In 2005 the National Film Registry added *San Francisco Earthquake and Fire, April 18, 1906*, a newsreel documentary made soon after the earthquake, to its list of American films worthy of preservation.
[src:andrew-lawson/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Worden's gelatin silver prints documenting the destruction were later collected by the Museum of Modern Art in New York, the San Francisco Museum of Modern Art, and the Oakland Museum of California.
[src:andrew-lawson/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] After the destruction, all that remained of the Alban N.
[src:andrew-lawson/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Towne mansion on Nob Hill were six marble columns and a lintel.
[src:andrew-lawson/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] When viewed from a certain angle, the empty porch perfectly framed the ruins of the smoldering City Hall.
[src:andrew-lawson/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] The haunting image became an icon of the 1906 earthquake, due largely to photographs by Worden.
[src:andrew-lawson/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] In 1909, the columns and lintel were relocated to Golden Gate Park, where, known as Portals of the Past, they became an enduring monument to the city's grief and a symbol of its endurance.
[src:andrew-lawson/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Copyright, Pillsbury Pictures, 18 April 1906.
[src:andrew-lawson/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Its wood interior burned, but its steel, concrete and stone frame survived.
[src:andrew-lawson/aapg-bulletin] The ***AAPG Bulletin*** is a monthly peer-reviewed scientific journal covering geosciences and associated technologies relating to the energy industry.
[src:andrew-lawson/aapg-bulletin] It is an official journal of the American Association of Petroleum Geologists.
[src:andrew-lawson/aapg-bulletin] The current editor-in-chief is Matthew J.
[src:andrew-lawson/aapg-bulletin] This journal is abstracted and/or indexed in: GeoRef, GEOBASE, Scopus, PubMed, Current Contents, and Web of Science.
[src:andrew-lawson/adolph-knopf] Knopf was a member of the National Academy of Sciences and the American Academy of Arts and Sciences.
[src:andrew-lawson/adolph-knopf] He served as president of the Geological Society of America in 1944 and received its Penrose Medal in 1959.
[src:andrew-lawson/adolph-knopf] His second wife, Eleanora Knopf, was a notable geologist and frequent collaborator.
[src:andrew-lawson/adolph-knopf] Knopf was born December 2, 1882, in San Francisco, California, to German American immigrants.
[src:andrew-lawson/adolph-knopf] He grew up with his family on a ranch near Woodside, California.
[src:andrew-lawson/adolph-knopf] Knopf entered the University of California, Berkeley, where he became a student of petrology under Andrew Lawson.
[src:andrew-lawson/adolph-knopf] He earned a Bachelor of Science degree in mining geology in 1904 and a Master of Science degree in 1905.
[src:andrew-lawson/adolph-knopf] That same year he spent the first of six summers surveying the mineral deposits of Alaska for the United States Geological Survey (USGS).
[src:andrew-lawson/adolph-knopf] In 1906 he moved to Washington, D.C., to work for the USGS full-time.
[src:andrew-lawson/adolph-knopf] The Alaskan Division, of which Knopf was one of about a dozen members, was considered the best geologic group in the USGS at that time.
[src:andrew-lawson/adolph-knopf] Knopf's work on tin deposits in the Seward Peninsula became the basis of the dissertation for his Ph.D., which he received from Berkeley in 1909.
[src:andrew-lawson/adolph-knopf] In Alaska he also discovered the minerals hulsite and paigeite.
[src:andrew-lawson/adolph-knopf] In 1911 Knopf was promoted from assistant geologist to geologist.
[src:andrew-lawson/adolph-knopf] Over the next nine years he undertook a series of field projects for the USGS, beginning with the mining district in Montana that includes the Boulder Batholith and continuing to other western states including Nevada and California.
[src:andrew-lawson/adolph-knopf] In the latter state he surveyed the Gold Country.
[src:andrew-lawson/adolph-knopf] After discovering that universities on the eastern seaboard were paying about double the USGS salaries, Knopf left the USGS for a teaching position, and a number of his colleagues followed suit.
[src:andrew-lawson/adolph-knopf] Knopf began at Yale University in January 1920.
[src:andrew-lawson/adolph-knopf] He encouraged students to work with the USGS as he had done; this helped mitigate the agency's brain drain following the departures.
[src:andrew-lawson/adolph-knopf] Knopf began at Yale as an associate professor but was promoted to full professor in 1923.
[src:andrew-lawson/adolph-knopf] He was named the Silliman Professor of Geology in 1937 and a Sterling Professor in 1938.
[src:andrew-lawson/adolph-knopf] He was director of graduate studies from 1933 until his retirement from Yale in 1951.
[src:andrew-lawson/adolph-knopf] Upon retiring he returned to his native Woodside, California, settling not far from his family's old ranch.
[src:andrew-lawson/adolph-knopf] There he accepted a visiting appointment at the Stanford University School of Earth Sciences, where he remained until his death in 1966.
[src:andrew-lawson/adolph-knopf] Knopf's field work continued through his Yale and Stanford appointments, again with a focus on western states.
[src:andrew-lawson/adolph-knopf] He continued his work in the Boulder Batholith and investigated intrusive igneous rock bodies in the Spanish Peaks in Colorado.
[src:andrew-lawson/adolph-knopf] He also contributed to the emerging field of geochronology, putting lower bounds of 2 billion years and later 4.5 billion years on the age of the Earth.
[src:andrew-lawson/adolph-knopf] Knopf was elected to the National Academy of Sciences in 1931.
[src:andrew-lawson/adolph-knopf] He was also a Fellow of the American Academy of Arts and Sciences and of the Geological Society of America.
[src:andrew-lawson/adolph-knopf] He was president of the Geological Society of America in 1944, and he received the Penrose Medal in 1959.
[src:andrew-lawson/adolph-knopf] In 1937 he was vice president of the Society of Economic Geologists.
[src:andrew-lawson/adolph-knopf] In 1908 Knopf married Agnes Burchard Dillon.
[src:andrew-lawson/adolph-knopf] They had three daughters and one son, though one of the daughters died in infancy.
[src:andrew-lawson/adolph-knopf] Agnes died in 1918 in that year's flu pandemic.
[src:andrew-lawson/adolph-knopf] In June 1920, Knopf married fellow USGS geologist Eleanora Frances Bliss, who as Eleanora Knopf became a frequent collaborator and travel companion.
[src:andrew-lawson/adolph-knopf] When Adolph moved to Yale, which did not then hire women, Eleanora worked out of Adolph's office, teaching private classes and still accepting USGS assignments.
[src:andrew-lawson/adolph-knopf] When they moved to California, Stanford hired her as a research associate.
[src:andrew-lawson/adolph-knopf] Knopf died November 23, 1966, in Palo Alto, California.
[src:andrew-lawson/adolph-knopf] In his will he endowed a chaired professorship at Yale.
[src:andrew-lawson/adolph-knopf] The sitting Adolph Knopf Professor of Petrology is Shun-ichiro Karato.
[src:andrew-lawson/adolph-knopf] Adolph and Eleanora Knopf also endowed a graduate fellowship in petrology at Stanford.
[src:andrew-lawson/adolph-knopf] Mount Adolph Knopf in Juneau Borough, Alaska is named after him.
[src:andrew-lawson/alameda-county-california] The Spanish word *alameda* means either "a grove of poplar trees or a tree lined street".
[src:andrew-lawson/alameda-county-california] The name was originally used to describe the Arroyo de la Alameda; the willow and sycamore trees along the banks of the river reminded the early Spanish explorers of a road lined with trees.
[src:andrew-lawson/alameda-county-california] Alameda County is part of the San Francisco–Oakland–Berkeley, CA Metropolitan Statistical Area, and the San Jose–San Francisco–Oakland, CA Combined Statistical Area.
[src:andrew-lawson/alameda-county-california] The county was formed on March 25, 1853, from a large portion of Contra Costa County and a smaller portion of Santa Clara County.
[src:andrew-lawson/alameda-county-california] The county seat at the time of the county's formation was located at Alvarado, now part of Union City.
[src:andrew-lawson/alameda-county-california] In 1856, it was moved to San Leandro, where the county courthouse was destroyed by the devastating 1868 quake on the Hayward Fault.
[src:andrew-lawson/alameda-county-california] The county seat was then re-established in the town of Brooklyn from 1872 to 1875.
[src:andrew-lawson/alameda-county-california] Brooklyn is now part of Oakland, which has been the county seat since 1873.
[src:andrew-lawson/alameda-county-california] Much of what is now an intensively urban region was initially developed as a trolley car suburb of San Francisco in the late 19th and early 20th centuries.
[src:andrew-lawson/alameda-county-california] The Key System moved commuters to and from the Key System Mole, where ferries bridged the gap across San Francisco Bay.
[src:andrew-lawson/alameda-county-california] The historical progression from Native American tribal lands to Spanish then Mexican ranches, then to farms, ranches, and orchards, then to multiple city centers and suburbs, is shared with the adjacent and closely associated Contra Costa County.
[src:andrew-lawson/alameda-county-california] The Government of Alameda County is defined and authorized under the California Constitution, California law, and the Charter of the County of Alameda.
[src:andrew-lawson/alameda-county-california] Much of the Government of California is in practice the responsibility of county governments such as the Government of Alameda County, while municipalities such as the City of Oakland and the City of Berkeley provide additional, often non-essential services.
[src:andrew-lawson/alameda-county-california] The County government provides countywide services such as elections and voter registration, law enforcement, jails, vital records, property records, tax collection, and public health.
[src:andrew-lawson/alameda-county-california] In addition it is the local government for all unincorporated areas, and provides services such as law enforcement to some incorporated cities under a contract arrangement.
[src:andrew-lawson/alameda-county-california] In addition, several entities of the government of California have jurisdiction conterminous with Alameda County, such as the Alameda County Superior Court.
[src:andrew-lawson/alameda-county-california] The Board elects a president who presides at all meetings of the Board and appoints committees to handle work involving the major programs of the county.
[src:andrew-lawson/alameda-county-california] If the president is absent for a meeting, the vice president shall be responsible.
[src:andrew-lawson/alameda-county-california] A Board election occurs every two years for these positions.
[src:andrew-lawson/alameda-county-california] Supervisor Carson is serving currently as president; Supervisor Miley is vice president.
[src:andrew-lawson/alameda-county-california] The county's law enforcement is overseen by an elected Sheriff/Coroner and an elected District Attorney.
[src:andrew-lawson/alameda-county-california] The District Attorney's office is responsible for prosecuting all criminal violations of the laws of the state of California, the county, or its constituent municipalities, in the Alameda County Superior Court.
[src:andrew-lawson/alameda-county-california] The current Sheriff is Yesenia Sanchez, who was elected in 2022, succeeding Greg Ahern, who had served in the post for 16 years.
[src:andrew-lawson/alameda-county-california] The Sheriff's Office operates two jails: Santa Rita Jail in Dublin, and Glenn E.
[src:andrew-lawson/alameda-county-california] Dyer Detention Facility in downtown Oakland.
[src:andrew-lawson/alameda-county-california] O'Malley was appointed Alameda County district attorney after Tom Orloff retired.
[src:andrew-lawson/alameda-county-california] She served two terms and did not run for reelection in 2022.
[src:andrew-lawson/alameda-county-california] Pamela Price was elected as district attorney in 2022.
[src:andrew-lawson/alameda-county-california] The Alameda County Fire Department (ACFD) was formed on July 1, 1993, as a dependent district, with the Board of Supervisors as its governing body.
[src:andrew-lawson/alameda-county-california] Municipal and specialized fire departments have been consolidated into the ACFD over the years.
[src:andrew-lawson/alameda-county-california] 1993 brought in the Castro Valley and Eden Consolidated FD, and the County Fire Patrol.
[src:andrew-lawson/alameda-county-california] San Leandro joined in 1995, Dublin in 1997, Lawrence Berkeley National Laboratory in 2002, Lawrence Livermore National Laboratory in 2007, The Alameda County Regional Emergency Communications Center in 2008, and Newark and Union City in 2010.
[src:andrew-lawson/alameda-county-california] The Alameda County Water District is a special district within Alameda County created to distribute water, but it is not operated by Alameda County administrators.
[src:andrew-lawson/alameda-county-california] It is operated by an elected board of directors.
[src:andrew-lawson/alameda-county-california] Alameda County Superior Court operates in twelve separate locations throughout the county, with its central René C.
[src:andrew-lawson/alameda-county-california] Davidson Courthouse located in Oakland near Lake Merritt.
[src:andrew-lawson/alameda-county-california] Most major criminal trials and complex civil cases are heard at this location or in courtrooms within the County Administration Building across the street.
[src:andrew-lawson/alameda-county-california] Since 1932, Alameda County has been a stronghold of the Democratic Party, with Dwight Eisenhower being the only Republican presidential nominee to have carried the county since.
[src:andrew-lawson/alameda-county-california] Prior to 1932, the county had been a Republican stronghold.
[src:andrew-lawson/alameda-county-california] Even when Ronald Reagan won the national popular vote by an 18.3% margin in 1984, Walter Mondale won Alameda County by a larger margin.
[src:andrew-lawson/alameda-county-california] In 2004 it voted for John Kerry, who won over 75% of the vote.
[src:andrew-lawson/alameda-county-california] Bush in 1988 was the last Republican to break 30% of the county's vote and Ronald Reagan in 1984 was the last to break 40% of the vote (carrying 40.01%).
[src:andrew-lawson/alameda-county-california] On November 4, 2008, Alameda County voted 61.92% against Proposition 8, which won statewide, and which amended the California Constitution to ban same-sex marriage.
[src:andrew-lawson/alameda-county-california] The county garnered the sixth highest "no" vote, by percentage, of all California counties, and was the second largest county, by total voter turnout, to vote against it.
[src:andrew-lawson/alameda-county-california] Census Bureau, the county has a total area of 821 square miles (2,130 km2), of which 739 square miles (1,910 km2) is land and 82 square miles (210 km2) (10%) is water.
[src:andrew-lawson/alameda-county-california] The San Francisco Bay borders the county on the west.
[src:andrew-lawson/alameda-county-california] The crest of the Berkeley Hills forms part of the northeastern boundary and reaches into the center of the county.
[src:andrew-lawson/alameda-county-california] A coastal plain several miles wide lines the bay; and is Oakland's most populous region.
[src:andrew-lawson/alameda-county-california] Livermore Valley lies in the eastern part of the county.
[src:andrew-lawson/alameda-county-california] Amador Valley abuts the western edge of Livermore Valley and continues west to the Pleasanton Ridge.
[src:andrew-lawson/alameda-county-california] The ridges and valleys of the Diablo Range, containing the county's highest peaks, cover the very sparsely populated southeast portion of the county.
[src:andrew-lawson/alameda-county-california] The Hayward Fault, a major branch of the San Andreas Fault to the west, runs through the most populated parts of Alameda County, while the Calaveras Fault runs through the southeastern part of the county.
[src:andrew-lawson/alameda-county-california] The areas near the Bay itself have a maritime warm-summer Mediterranean climate, whereas behind the mountains, summers are significantly warmer.
[src:andrew-lawson/alameda-county-california] The climate charts below are for Oakland and inland Livermore.
[src:andrew-lawson/alameda-county-california] The City and County of San Francisco, California, borders the county on the west, and has a small land border with the city of Alameda, California due to land filling.
[src:andrew-lawson/alameda-county-california] Santa Clara County borders the county on the south.
[src:andrew-lawson/alameda-county-california] San Joaquin County borders the county on the east.
[src:andrew-lawson/alameda-county-california] Contra Costa County borders the county on the north.
[src:andrew-lawson/alameda-county-california] Stanislaus County borders the county on the easternmost end of its southern boundary for 250 feet (76 m).
[src:andrew-lawson/alameda-county-california] Note: the US Census treats Hispanic/Latino as an ethnic category.
[src:andrew-lawson/alameda-county-california] This table excludes Latinos from the racial categories and assigns them to a separate category.
[src:andrew-lawson/alameda-county-california] As of the 2020 census, the county had a population of 1,682,353.
[src:andrew-lawson/alameda-county-california] The median age was 37.7 years, 20.4% of residents were under the age of 18, and 14.3% of residents were 65 years of age or older.
[src:andrew-lawson/alameda-county-california] For every 100 females there were 96.1 males, and for every 100 females age 18 and over there were 94.0 males age 18 and over.
[src:andrew-lawson/alameda-county-california] The racial makeup of the county was 31.1% White, 9.8% Black or African American, 1.2% American Indian and Alaska Native, 32.4% Asian, 0.8% Native Hawaiian and Pacific Islander, 13.3% from some other race, and 11.3% from two or more races.
[src:andrew-lawson/alameda-county-california] Hispanic or Latino residents of any race comprised 23.4% of the population.
[src:andrew-lawson/alameda-county-california] The 2020 census shows Alameda as having one of the highest Asian percentages and being one of two counties in the continental US, along with neighboring Santa Clara County, California, to have an Asian plurality - consisting largely of Chinese, Indian and Filipino ancestry.
[src:andrew-lawson/alameda-county-california] 99.5% of residents lived in urban areas, while 0.5% lived in rural areas.
[src:andrew-lawson/alameda-county-california] There were 591,636 households in the county, of which 33.0% had children under the age of 18 living with them and 26.5% had a female householder with no spouse or partner present.
[src:andrew-lawson/alameda-county-california] About 24.1% of all households were made up of individuals and 9.0% had someone living alone who was 65 years of age or older.
[src:andrew-lawson/alameda-county-california] There were 621,958 housing units, of which 4.9% were vacant.
[src:andrew-lawson/alameda-county-california] Among occupied housing units, 51.8% were owner-occupied and 48.2% were renter-occupied.
[src:andrew-lawson/alameda-county-california] The homeowner vacancy rate was 0.8% and the rental vacancy rate was 4.8%.
[src:andrew-lawson/alameda-county-california] The 2010 United States census reported that Alameda County had a population of 1,510,271.
[src:andrew-lawson/alameda-county-california] The population density was 2,047.6 inhabitants per square mile (790.6/km2).
[src:andrew-lawson/alameda-county-california] As of the census of 2000, there were 1,443,741 people, 523,366 households, out of which 32.6% had children under the age of 18 living within them, 47.0% married couples living together, 13.0% had a female householder with no husband present, and 35.2% were non-families.
[src:andrew-lawson/alameda-county-california] 26.0% of all households were made up of individuals, and 7.3% had someone living alone who was 65 years of age or older.
[src:andrew-lawson/alameda-county-california] The average household size was 2.71 and the average family size was 3.31.
[src:andrew-lawson/alameda-county-california] In the county, the population was spread out, with 24.6% under the age of 18, 9.6% from 18 to 24, 33.9% from 25 to 44, 21.7% from 45 to 64, and 10.2% who were 65 years of age or older.
[src:andrew-lawson/alameda-county-california] For every 100 females there were 96.60 males.
[src:andrew-lawson/alameda-county-california] For every 100 females age 18 and over, there were 94.00 males.
[src:andrew-lawson/alameda-county-california] The median income for a household in the county was $55,946, and the median income for a family was $65,857 (these figures had risen to $66,430 and $81,341 respectively as of a 2007 estimate).
[src:andrew-lawson/alameda-county-california] Males had a median income of $47,425 versus $36,921 for females.
[src:andrew-lawson/alameda-county-california] The per capita income for the county was $26,680.
[src:andrew-lawson/alameda-county-california] About 7.7% of families and 11.0% of the population were below the poverty line, including 13.5% of those under age 18 and 8.1% of those age 65 or over.
[src:andrew-lawson/alameda-county-california] In 2000, the largest denominational group was the Catholics (with 306,437 adherents).
[src:andrew-lawson/alameda-county-california] The largest religious bodies were the Catholic Church (with 306,437 members) and Judaism (with 32,500 members).
[src:andrew-lawson/alameda-county-california] Asian Americans are the largest racial/ethnic group at 33.9% (excluding Asian Hispanics).
[src:andrew-lawson/alameda-county-california] The White population is the second largest racial category in Alameda County and includes the 8.1% of Hispanics who self-identify as White.
[src:andrew-lawson/alameda-county-california] The remainder of Hispanics self-identify as Other Race (57.3%), Multiracial (27.9%), American Indian and Alaskan Native (4.4%), Black (1.1%), Asian (0.9%), and Hawaiian and Pacific Islander (0.2%).
[src:andrew-lawson/alameda-county-california] The Black population continues to decline and at 9.1% (excluding Black Hispanics) is below the national average of 11.7% in 2024.
[src:andrew-lawson/alameda-county-california] The Black population peaked in the 1980 Census at 18.4%.
[src:andrew-lawson/alameda-county-california] Alameda county has the 2nd highest percentage of Black residents in California after Solano County at 13.4%.
[src:andrew-lawson/alameda-county-california] White Non-Hispanic Americans are the largest minority group at 23.6% of the population.
[src:andrew-lawson/alameda-county-california] By ethnicity, 23.6% of the total population is Hispanic-Latino (of any race) and 77.7% is Non-Hispanic (of any race).
[src:andrew-lawson/alameda-county-california] If treated as a category separate from race, Hispanics are the third largest minority group in Alameda County.
[src:andrew-lawson/alameda-county-california] If Hispanics are treated as a separate category from race, Alameda County's population was 30.4% White, 30.9% Asian, 22.3% Hispanic-Latino, 10.3% Black or African American, 0.5% Some Other Race, 0.3% Native American and Alaskan Native, 0.8% Pacific Islander and 4.4% from two or more races.
[src:andrew-lawson/alameda-county-california] The following table includes the number of incidents reported and the rate per 1,000 persons for each type of offense.
[src:andrew-lawson/alameda-county-california] The Alameda County Office of Education oversees seventeen K–12 school districts and one K–8 district in Alameda County.
[src:andrew-lawson/alameda-county-california] In all, there are approximately 10,000 teachers serving 225,000 students.
[src:andrew-lawson/alameda-county-california] The ACOE also services three community college districts with a total enrollment of approximately 55,000 students.
[src:andrew-lawson/alameda-county-california] The Alameda County Library operates libraries in the cities of Albany, Dublin, Fremont, Newark and Union City and the unincorporated communities of Castro Valley and San Lorenzo.
[src:andrew-lawson/alameda-county-california] The cities of Alameda, Berkeley, Hayward, Livermore, Oakland, San Leandro, and Pleasanton have their own library systems.
[src:andrew-lawson/alameda-county-california] Alameda County is home to the University of California, Berkeley, the flagship campus of the University of California system, and one of the largest and most prestigious research universities in the world.
[src:andrew-lawson/alameda-county-california] The Alameda County Arts Commission, a division of the county administration, under the California Arts Council, was created in 1965.
[src:andrew-lawson/alameda-county-california] Its fifteen appointed members act in an advisory capacity to the board of supervisors, in promoting the arts.
[src:andrew-lawson/alameda-county-california] The Oakland Museum of California has a substantial collection of California art works and historical artifacts.
[src:andrew-lawson/alameda-county-california] The annual county fair is held at the Alameda County Fairgrounds in Pleasanton.
[src:andrew-lawson/alameda-county-california] The fair runs for four weekends from June to July.
[src:andrew-lawson/alameda-county-california] Attractions include horse racing, carnival rides, 4-H exhibits, and live bands.
[src:andrew-lawson/alameda-county-california] There are more than 350 parks located within the county.
[src:andrew-lawson/alameda-county-california] Eastshore State Park is located partially along the bay shore of northern Alameda County.
[src:andrew-lawson/alameda-county-california] The San Francisco Bay Trail, a project of the Association of Bay Area Governments, will run along the bay shore of the county.
[src:andrew-lawson/alameda-county-california] The Hayward Area Recreation and Park District is the largest special park district in California.
[src:andrew-lawson/alameda-county-california] The main airport is the Oakland San Francisco Bay Airport, with two general aviation airports, the Hayward Executive Airport and Livermore Municipal Airport.
[src:andrew-lawson/alameda-county-california] Alameda Health System operates the public health system in Alameda County.
[src:andrew-lawson/alameda-county-california] It operates five hospitals (Alameda Hospital, Fairmont Hospital, Highland Hospital, John George Psychiatric Hospital, and San Leandro Hospital), and four primary care medical clinics (called ambulatory wellness centers) within the county.
[src:andrew-lawson/alameda-county-california] The Alameda County Community Food Bank nonprofit provides food bank resources to residents.
[src:andrew-lawson/alameda-county-california] The Family Emergency Shelter Coalition coordinates services for homeless families.
[src:andrew-lawson/alameda-county-california] The county has a large number of National Historic Places, as well as a number of California Historical Landmarks.
[src:andrew-lawson/alameda-county-california] Alameda has two sister county: Taoyuan County, Taiwan (now Taoyuan City) and Zhongshan in China.
[src:andrew-lawson/alameda-county-california] The population ranking of the following table is based on the 2020 census of Alameda County.
[src:andrew-lawson/albert-w-bally] Bally started his career at Shell Oil Company, retiring as Chief Geologist after 27 years in 1981.
[src:andrew-lawson/albert-w-bally] After retirement, he joined Rice University as chair of the Department of Geology and Geophysics.
[src:andrew-lawson/albert-w-bally] He remained active in the department until his death in 2019.
[src:andrew-lawson/albert-w-bally] In 1988, Bally was elected President of the Geological Society of America.
[src:andrew-lawson/alexander-winchell] Winchell graduated from the Wesleyan University of Middletown, Connecticut, in 1847.
[src:andrew-lawson/alexander-winchell] He then taught at Pennington Male Seminary of New Jersey, Amenia Seminary of New York (where he had previously been a student), an academy in Newbern, Alabama, and the Mesopotamia Female Seminary of Eutaw, the last of which was founded by him.
[src:andrew-lawson/alexander-winchell] He became president of the Masonic University at Selma, Alabama, in 1853.
[src:andrew-lawson/alexander-winchell] He was elected as a member of the American Philosophical Society in 1865.
[src:andrew-lawson/alexander-winchell] In 1854 Winchell entered the service of the University of Michigan as professor of physics and civil engineering.
[src:andrew-lawson/alexander-winchell] Eventually he became professor of geology and paleontology at Michigan.
[src:andrew-lawson/alexander-winchell] In 1859, Winchell was appointed as State Geologist of Michigan for the newly formed second geological survey of the state.
[src:andrew-lawson/alexander-winchell] He held the post until 1863 when the state did not appropriate funding to continue the survey.
[src:andrew-lawson/alexander-winchell] The survey was resumed in 1869, and Winchell was reappointed in April.
[src:andrew-lawson/alexander-winchell] Owing to conflicting opinions between Winchell and his superiors, he resigned in 1871.
[src:andrew-lawson/alexander-winchell] In 1863 Winchell took up a lease on a cotton plantation near Vicksburg, Mississippi, under a plan devised by Gen.
[src:andrew-lawson/alexander-winchell] Lorenzo Thomas to lease plantations along the Mississippi River to loyal men from the North, who would hire black laborers on terms prescribed by the army.
[src:andrew-lawson/alexander-winchell] Winchell organized the Ann Arbor Cotton Company and sold stock to the university's president, whereupon he received a leave of absence to engage in cotton planting.
[src:andrew-lawson/alexander-winchell] General Thomas set wages at a low level ($7 per month for men, $5 for women, minus the cost of medical attention and clothing).
[src:andrew-lawson/alexander-winchell] Even then, many lessees defrauded the freedmen of their earnings.
[src:andrew-lawson/alexander-winchell] In the winter of 1863–64, the Treasury Department briefly assumed control of the Mississippi Valley labor system, mandated a substantial increase in black wages, and contemplated leasing the plantations directly to the freedmen.
[src:andrew-lawson/alexander-winchell] The venture brought him only problems, and after he returned to Michigan in 1864, his brother Martin, who was managing the plantation, was killed by guerrillas.
[src:andrew-lawson/alexander-winchell] In 1872, he was appointed chancellor of Syracuse University.
[src:andrew-lawson/alexander-winchell] The depression of 1873 affected both his personal finances and those of Syracuse, and these troubles led him to resign this position in 1874.
[src:andrew-lawson/alexander-winchell] In 1875, he worked as a professor of geology and zoology at Vanderbilt University.
[src:andrew-lawson/alexander-winchell] There, his views on evolution, as expressed in his book *Adamites and Preadamites: or, A Popular Discussion* (1878), were not acceptable to the University administration because they diverged from Biblical teaching.
[src:andrew-lawson/alexander-winchell] Today the views on the "inferiority of the Negro" (quote from his 1878 book) would probably have been the focus of controversy.
[src:andrew-lawson/alexander-winchell] In any case, he was obligated to resign in 1878.
[src:andrew-lawson/alexander-winchell] In 1888, he co-founded the Geological Society of America in Ithaca, New York along with John J.
[src:andrew-lawson/alexander-winchell] He served as the 3rd president of GSA in 1891.
[src:andrew-lawson/alexander-winchell] He then returned to the University of Michigan, where he was professor of geology and paleontology.
[src:andrew-lawson/alexander-winchell] His work in geology was not so significant as his teaching and popular lectures and writing in this field.
[src:andrew-lawson/alexander-winchell] He was much concerned with reconciling science and religion.
[src:andrew-lawson/alexander-winchell] He was an advocate of theistic evolution.
[src:andrew-lawson/alexander-winchell] The fish **Clear chub** *Hybopsis winchelli* (Girard, 1856) is named after him.
[src:andrew-lawson/alexander-winchell] The University of Michigan named a wing of the West Quad dormitory after Winchell, and Ann Arbor honored him with Winchell Park, a neighborhood park on the city's east side.
[src:andrew-lawson/alexander-winchell] Winchell's name was removed from the dormitory in 2018, and the park was renamed after former Ann Arbor Public Schools board president Harold J.
[src:andrew-lawson/alexander-winchell] In removing Winchell's name, the university described his *Preadamites* as an "unambiguously racist" work.
[src:andrew-lawson/alfred-church-lane] Lane was educated at Harvard University and received his A.B. degree in 1883.
[src:andrew-lawson/alfred-church-lane] Between 1883 and 1885 he taught mathematics at Harvard, then studied at the University of Heidelberg until 1887 before returning to Harvard to earn his Ph.D. in 1888.
[src:andrew-lawson/alfred-church-lane] The following year he joined the Michigan State Geologic Survey as a petrographer, and he remained in that post into 1892 while also serving as an instructor at the Michigan College of Mines.
[src:andrew-lawson/alfred-church-lane] He became assistant state geologist for Michigan in 1892, and from 1899 to 1909 he was the state geologist.
[src:andrew-lawson/alfred-church-lane] Finally, he joined Tufts College in 1892, becoming the Pearson professor of geology and mineralogy.
[src:andrew-lawson/alfred-church-lane] He retired from the college in 1936 as professor emeritus.
[src:andrew-lawson/alfred-church-lane] While at Tufts, he served as vice president of the AAAS Division of Geology in 1907.
[src:andrew-lawson/alfred-church-lane] He received an honorary D.Sc. from Tufts in 1913.
[src:andrew-lawson/alfred-church-lane] From 1922 and 1946 he was chairman for the Committee on the Measurement of Geologic Time for the National Research Council.
[src:andrew-lawson/alfred-church-lane] He served as a member of the Board of Visitors at Harvard Observatory in 1924.
[src:andrew-lawson/alfred-church-lane] Alfred Lane was appointed as consultant of science to the Library of Congress in 1929; the first person to hold that post.
[src:andrew-lawson/alfred-church-lane] In 1931, he was president of the Geological Society of America.
[src:andrew-lawson/alfred-church-lane] He was awarded the Ballou Medal by Tufts College in 1940 for "distinguished service to education and the nation".
[src:andrew-lawson/alfred-church-lane] During his career, he authored 1,087 publications.
[src:andrew-lawson/andrew-lawson] Lawson was born on July 25, 1861, in Anstruther, Scotland.
[src:andrew-lawson/andrew-lawson] He moved to Hamilton, Ontario, Canada with his parents at age six.
[src:andrew-lawson/andrew-lawson] In 1883, he received his B.A. degree in natural science from the University of Toronto.
[src:andrew-lawson/andrew-lawson] He worked for the Geological Survey of Canada while pursuing his graduate degrees.
[src:andrew-lawson/andrew-lawson] He received his M.A. from the University of Toronto in 1885, and his Ph.D. from Johns Hopkins University in 1888.
[src:andrew-lawson/andrew-lawson] In 1890, he left the Geological Survey of Canada to work as a consulting geologist in Vancouver.
[src:andrew-lawson/andrew-lawson] In October of the same year, he accepted a position as assistant professor of Mineralogy and Geology at the University of California in Berkeley.
[src:andrew-lawson/andrew-lawson] He became a full professor in 1892, and a professor emeritus from 1928 to his death on June 16, 1952.
[src:andrew-lawson/andrew-lawson] Lawson was elected to the American Academy of Arts and Sciences in 1915, the United States National Academy of Sciences in 1924, and the American Philosophical Society in 1925.
[src:andrew-lawson/andrew-lawson] He was president of the Geological Society of America in 1926.
[src:andrew-lawson/andrew-lawson] He was a consulting geologist for the construction of the Golden Gate Bridge in the 1930s.
[src:andrew-lawson/andrew-lawson] His home in the La Loma Park area of the Berkeley Hills in Berkeley, California, called the "Andrew Cowper Lawson House" (1908), was especially designed for him by noted architect Bernard Maybeck to withstand earthquakes.
[src:andrew-lawson/andrew-lawson] The house is an official city designated Berkeley Landmark.
[src:andrew-lawson/andrew-lawson] The mineral Lawsonite is named for him, as is the Lawson Adit, originally a mining construction research tunnel on UC Berkeley's campus.
[src:andrew-lawson/andrew-lawson] 13,165 feet) in Sequoia National Park was officially named after him in 1976.
[src:andrew-lawson/andrew-lawson] 1,128 feet), located west of the Briones Hills in Contra Costa County, California, is named for him.
